turn.2: With the change in ownership, SJR Communications changed WCJW's call letters to WQAL on May 12, 1971..
turn.4: The new call letters represented "Quality Music" or "Quality Listening." SJR handed off most of its broadcasting assets, including WQAL, to Gulf United Broadcasting in 1981.
turn.5: Are there any other interesting aspects about this article?
turn.6: In October 1984, Gulf sold WQAL to WIN Communications, a locally-run company, for $4.8 million..
turn.7: What did they do after winning?
turn.8: WQAL's format throughout the 1970s and 1980s was beautiful music as "Easy 104 WQAL. " The station featured some of Cleveland radio's best-known personalities, including "Tall" Ted Hallaman, James "Jay Lynn" Threatt, Ed Fisher, Al James, Frank Micale, and David Mark.
